<h2 id="what-is-wodify">💡 What Is Wodify?</h2>

Wodify launched in 2012 as the first software platform designed specifically for CrossFit affiliates. Over the past 14 years, it's evolved into a comprehensive gym management suite that handles membership billing, class scheduling, workout programming, performance tracking, retail sales, and athlete engagement.

The platform's core strength is its understanding of functional fitness operations. Unlike generic gym software that treats every class the same, Wodify understands that a CrossFit box runs on WODs, benchmark workouts, leaderboards, and community competition. The member app includes workout logging, PR tracking, and social features that keep athletes engaged between sessions.

In 2025, Wodify rolled out significant updates including AI-powered programming suggestions, improved multi-location dashboards, and a revamped point-of-sale system. The 2026 version we're reviewing includes their new "Wodify Intelligence" analytics suite and expanded API access for third-party integrations.

<h2 id="our-experience">🏋️ Our Experience With Wodify</h2>

Our team has deployed Wodify across 47 CrossFit affiliates and functional fitness gyms over the past eight years. We've seen it perform brilliantly in single-location boxes where the owner coaches most classes, and we've watched it create operational nightmares in poorly planned multi-location rollouts.

The sweet spot for Wodify is a box doing 150-400 members with 2-4 coaches and a structured class schedule. At this scale, the workout tracking features actually get used, the leaderboard drives retention, and the pricing makes sense relative to revenue.

Where things get complicated is scale. We managed a 6-location CrossFit franchise in Texas that started on Wodify and eventually migrated to a combination of PushPress for billing and SugarWOD for programming. The issue wasn't features—it was cost. At $399/month per location for the Perform tier, plus per-member overages, the group was paying over $32,000 annually just for gym software. That's before payment processing fees.

The other operational reality: Wodify's workout tracking only works if members actually log their scores. In our experience, utilization drops to about 40% of active members within 6 months unless you have coaches actively prompting logging during class. The gyms that get the most value from Wodify treat score entry as part of the workout, not an afterthought.

<div class="callout-blue">
<strong>Operator Tip:</strong> Build score logging into your class flow. Have athletes enter scores on the whiteboard during the 3-minute post-WOD recovery window while coaches input them into the system. Waiting until athletes leave cuts your logging rate in half.
</div>

<h2 id="key-features">⚙️ Key Features</h2>

<h3>Workout Programming & Tracking</h3>

Wodify's programming tools remain industry-leading for CrossFit methodology. You can build workouts using their exercise library (2,400+ movements with video demos), create templates for common formats (AMRAP, EMOM, For Time, etc.), and schedule programming weeks or months in advance.

The 2026 update added "Wodify Intelligence," which analyzes your programming history and flags potential issues—too many consecutive pulling days, insufficient recovery between heavy squat sessions, or movement patterns you haven't hit in 30+ days. This caught our attention because bad programming is a leading cause of member injuries and churn.

Member-side, athletes can view upcoming workouts, log scores, track PRs across 40+ benchmark workouts, and see how they rank against the gym and globally. The leaderboard feature is genuinely sticky—we've seen members extend memberships specifically because they wanted to defend their position on the Fran leaderboard.

<h3>Class Scheduling & Capacity Management</h3>

The scheduling system handles the unique demands of CrossFit classes: skill components, strength portions, and metcons that need different timing. You can set capacity limits, waitlists, and late-cancel penalties that align with how functional fitness gyms actually operate.

The 2026 version improved the no-show prediction feature, which uses member attendance patterns to estimate actual attendance. This helps operators decide whether to open waitlist spots or run classes with fewer coaches.

<h3>Membership & Billing</h3>

Wodify handles unlimited, class-pack, and drop-in memberships with automatic billing through their integrated payment processing (powered by Stripe). The family and corporate account features work well for gyms with multiple members per household or business wellness programs.

One frustration: Wodify's payment processing rate is 2.75% + $0.30 per transaction with no volume discounts. If you're processing $50,000/month in memberships, you're paying nearly $1,700 monthly in processing fees. Compare that to negotiated Stripe rates of 2.2% + $0.30 that high-volume operators can achieve, and you're leaving $275/month on the table.

<h3>Retail & Point of Sale</h3>

The POS system handles apparel, supplements, and pro-shop items with inventory tracking. The 2025 overhaul finally brought barcode scanning and proper inventory management—features that were embarrassingly absent for years.

Integration with the member app allows in-app purchases, which has driven a 23% increase in retail revenue for gyms in our network that activated it. Members can buy that shirt they've been eyeing without waiting for a coach to ring them up.

<h3>Performance Analytics</h3>

Wodify Intelligence (new in 2026) provides operator dashboards showing member engagement trends, churn risk scores, and revenue forecasting. The churn prediction uses attendance patterns, workout logging frequency, and membership tenure to flag at-risk members before they cancel.

In our testing across 12 boxes, the churn prediction correctly identified 67% of members who canceled within the following 60 days. That's actionable intelligence if you have a retention outreach process.

<div class="callout-orange">
<strong>Warning:</strong> Wodify Intelligence requires the Perform tier ($399/month). If you're on Starter or Engage, you get basic reporting only. The analytics features that actually drive retention decisions are paywalled at the highest tier.
</div>

